<taxonomicName authorityName="Olivier" authorityYear="1811" box="[744,864,1923,1949]" genus="Mylabris" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="bipunctata">
<emphasis box="[744,864,1923,1949]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">bipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); Al Aïn area (
<bibRefCitation author="Gillet, M. P. T. &amp; Gillet, J." box="[1032,1261,1923,1949]" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" pagination="20 - 21" refId="ref33845" refString="Gillet, M. P. T. &amp; Gillet, J. (1996) A large blister beetle Mylabris maculiventris Klug, 1845 from Al Ain and neighbouring Oman (Coleoptera: Meloidae). Tribulus, 6, 20 - 21." type="journal article" year="1996">Gillet &amp; Gillet 1996</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Olivier" authorityYear="1811" box="[1299,1419,1923,1949]" genus="Mylabris" kingdom="Animalia" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" rank="species" species="bipunctata">
<emphasis box="[1299,1419,1923,1949]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">bipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); Wadi Bih; Wadi Shawkah (Batelka &amp; Geistardt 2009 as 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1811" box="[780,911,1959,1985]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Hycleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="23" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bipunctatus">
<emphasis box="[780,911,1959,1985]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="23">bipunctatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,152,683]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,152,179]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Description.</emphasis>
Body length 12–16.5 mm. Body black, elytra yellowish bright brown, sometimes red, with black pattern. Head subquadrate; male antennomere III (
<figureCitation box="[711,792,189,215]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–83" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1564,1589]" captionTargetBox="[181,1404,667,1533]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[177,1410,663,1539]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 77–83. Hycleus pirata Bologna &amp; Turco: 77. male antenna; 78. female antenna; 79. tegmen, ventral view; 80. tegmen, lateral view; 81. aedeagus, lateral view; 82. mesosternum; 83. elytral pattern. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887797" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887797/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 77</figureCitation>
) less than half longer than IV, V–VIII transverse and widened, IX–X narrower than VIII, male XI narrower and longer than X; in female (
<figureCitation box="[1055,1136,225,251]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–83" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1564,1589]" captionTargetBox="[181,1404,667,1533]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[177,1410,663,1539]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 77–83. Hycleus pirata Bologna &amp; Turco: 77. male antenna; 78. female antenna; 79. tegmen, ventral view; 80. tegmen, lateral view; 81. aedeagus, lateral view; 82. mesosternum; 83. elytral pattern. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887797" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887797/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 78</figureCitation>
) shorter than X. Pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[160,241,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURES 13–24" captionStartId="6.[151,262,1296,1321]" captionTargetBox="[223,1367,188,1264]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[220,1368,181,1271]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 13–24. Head and pronotum of: 13. Hycleus apicipennis; 14. H. balteatus; 15 H. bipunctatus; 16. H. cingulatus; 17. H. colligatus; 18. H. hayki; 19. H. lindbergi; 20. H. pirata; 21. H. schauffelei; 22. H. sexmaculatus; 23. H. tenuepictus; 24. H. trianguliferus." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887777" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887777/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 20</figureCitation>
) longer than wide, with anterior depression; mesosternum as in 
<figureCitation box="[961,1044,261,287]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–83" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1564,1589]" captionTargetBox="[181,1404,667,1533]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[177,1410,663,1539]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 77–83. Hycleus pirata Bologna &amp; Turco: 77. male antenna; 78. female antenna; 79. tegmen, ventral view; 80. tegmen, lateral view; 81. aedeagus, lateral view; 82. mesosternum; 83. elytral pattern. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887797" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887797/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 82</figureCitation>
. Each elytron with two black spots on anterior third, one sinuate middle fascia, and one black oblique fascia on apical part (
<figureCitation box="[1137,1220,297,323]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–83" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1564,1589]" captionTargetBox="[181,1404,667,1533]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[177,1410,663,1539]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 77–83. Hycleus pirata Bologna &amp; Turco: 77. male antenna; 78. female antenna; 79. tegmen, ventral view; 80. tegmen, lateral view; 81. aedeagus, lateral view; 82. mesosternum; 83. elytral pattern. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887797" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887797/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 83</figureCitation>
). Male last ventrite regularly concave and depressed, posterior margin with a wide and deep middle emargination; aedeagus (
<figureCitation box="[1346,1428,333,359]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–83" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1564,1589]" captionTargetBox="[181,1404,667,1533]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[177,1410,663,1539]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 77–83. Hycleus pirata Bologna &amp; Turco: 77. male antenna; 78. female antenna; 79. tegmen, ventral view; 80. tegmen, lateral view; 81. aedeagus, lateral view; 82. mesosternum; 83. elytral pattern. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887797" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887797/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Fig. 81</figureCitation>
) with endophallic hook narrow, distal aedeagal hook curved, far from proximal one and close to apex, proximal hook slightly curved; gonoforceps (
<figureCitation box="[494,625,405,431]" captionStart="FIGURES 77–83" captionStartId="22.[151,264,1564,1589]" captionTargetBox="[181,1404,667,1533]" captionTargetId="figure@22.[177,1410,663,1539]" captionTargetPageId="22" captionText="FIGURES 77–83. Hycleus pirata Bologna &amp; Turco: 77. male antenna; 78. female antenna; 79. tegmen, ventral view; 80. tegmen, lateral view; 81. aedeagus, lateral view; 82. mesosternum; 83. elytral pattern. Scale bar: 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3887797" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3887797/files/figure.png" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Figs 79–80</figureCitation>
) narrow and elongate both in ventral and lateral view (see 
<bibRefCitation author="Bologna, M. A. &amp; Turco, F." pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref32438" refString="Bologna, M. A. &amp; Turco, F. (2007) The Meloidae (Coleoptera) of the United Arab Emirates with an updated Arabian checklist. Zootaxa, 1625 (1), 1 - 33. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1625.1.1" type="journal article" year="2007">Bologna &amp; Turco 2007</bibRefCitation>
for a detailed description).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,152,683]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,446,476,503]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Taxonomic remarks.</emphasis>
This species resembles 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Reiche" baseAuthorityYear="1866" box="[718,882,478,503]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Hycleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicipennis">
<emphasis box="[718,882,478,503]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. apicipennis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
but it can be distinguished by the elongate shape of antennomere IV, which is subequal in length to V, the shape of last male antennomere, which is strikingly curved, and by the male genitalia. The shape of last antennomere is also very similar to that of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Serri &amp; Bologna &amp; Riccieri" authorityYear="2020" box="[1118,1213,549,575]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Hycleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hayki">
<emphasis box="[1118,1213,549,575]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. hayki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Olivier" baseAuthorityYear="1811" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Hycleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sexmaculatus">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. sexmaculatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bologna &amp; Turco" authorityYear="2007" box="[262,365,586,611]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Hycleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pirata">
<emphasis box="[262,365,586,611]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. pirata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs because of the pronotum and aedeagus shape.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="24" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="23.[151,1437,152,683]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,353,620,647]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Distribution.</emphasis>
This species seems to have restricted distribution in the 
<collectingCountry box="[988,1233,621,647]" name="United Arab Emirates" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">United Arab Emirates</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1287,1355,621,647]" name="Oman" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Oman</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Bologna, M. A. &amp; Turco, F." pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="1 - 33" refId="ref32438" refString="Bologna, M. A. &amp; Turco, F. (2007) The Meloidae (Coleoptera) of the United Arab Emirates with an updated Arabian checklist. Zootaxa, 1625 (1), 1 - 33. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1625.1.1" type="journal article" year="2007">Bologna &amp; Turco 2007</bibRefCitation>
). The record of this species from south 
<collectingCountry box="[802,847,657,683]" name="Iran" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">Iran</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Serri, S." box="[862,983,656,683]" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" pagination="232 - 237" refId="ref37243" refString="Serri, S. (2015) Blister beetles (Coleoptera: Meloidae) of Southwest Iran. Proceedings of the 1 st Iranian International Congress of Entomology, 2015, 232 - 237." type="journal article" year="2015">Serri 2015</bibRefCitation>
) refers to the new species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Serri &amp; Bologna &amp; Riccieri" authorityYear="2020" box="[1280,1375,657,683]" class="Insecta" family="Meloidae" genus="Hycleus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="24" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="hayki">
<emphasis box="[1280,1375,657,683]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="24">H. hayki</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
